WEBVTT

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:05.759
In our last session, we built our first

00:00:02.560 --> 00:00:08.400
MLP. We saw that a simple shallow MLP

00:00:05.759 --> 00:00:11.040
works fine, but when we try to make it

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:13.840
deeper, we run into the vanishing

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:15.920
gradient problem and our model failed to

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:18.240
learn. In this video, we're going to

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:21.359
build on that knowledge. Our goal is to

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:23.359
construct a robust, flexible, advanced

00:00:21.359 --> 00:00:26.160
MLP. We'll introduce several key

00:00:23.359 --> 00:00:29.519
techniques used in modern deep learning

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:31.599
such as better weight initialization

00:00:29.519 --> 00:00:33.920
and normalization to make our deep

00:00:31.599 --> 00:00:36.640
models train efficiently. We'll treat

00:00:33.920 --> 00:00:39.440
this as a scientific experiment also

00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:41.920
known as an ablation study to see which

00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:44.160
components give us the biggest

00:00:41.920 --> 00:00:47.039
performance boost. Let's start by

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:49.680
looking at our initial setup here. And

00:00:47.039 --> 00:00:52.160
if you notice there is a new one here

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:54.160
utils which is a Python file that I

00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:56.000
created and it contains all of the

00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:59.199
helper functions that I'm going to use

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.600
for plotting running diagnostics and

00:00:59.199 --> 00:01:04.080
visualization of the the weights of the

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:06.560
learned weights. Uh this way uh I'm

00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:08.960
trying to keep the the main script clean

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:11.760
and we want to focus on the core logic

00:01:08.960 --> 00:01:15.200
of the model and the experiment. Okay.

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:18.000
So next uh in the data preparation I

00:01:15.200 --> 00:01:20.159
added another step that basically

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.400
normalized the input data to have a mean

00:01:20.159 --> 00:01:25.439
of zero and a standard deviation of one.

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:27.759
Uh this simple step makes the training

00:01:25.439 --> 00:01:30.560
process significantly more stable and

00:01:27.759 --> 00:01:33.360
often faster. Normalization creates a a

00:01:30.560 --> 00:01:36.400
much smoother optimization landscape and

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:38.400
the optimizer uh can easily navigate

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:41.119
through this well- behaved landscape

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:42.880
compared to before. Moreover, it um

00:01:41.119 --> 00:01:45.759
basically ensures all of the input

00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:49.119
features are on a comparable scale.

00:01:45.759 --> 00:01:51.759
Prevents uh some weights from needing to

00:01:49.119 --> 00:01:53.759
learn extremely large or small values.

00:01:51.759 --> 00:01:56.159
So with that, let's go ahead and write

00:01:53.759 --> 00:02:00.479
our model class. We are going to call it

00:01:56.159 --> 00:02:02.560
advanced MLP. It's of course going to

00:02:00.479 --> 00:02:05.119
inherit all of the good goodies in an

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:08.399
end module. So this is the init method

00:02:05.119 --> 00:02:11.280
that I wrote uh where I added a few

00:02:08.399 --> 00:02:14.720
